Others agree. At the end of August, before the Gorman announcement, LightSh=
ed Partners=E2=80=99 Rich Greenfield and Brandon Ross offered an interestin=
g prelude about the topic on their podcast. Like many others, and in accord=
ance with the prevailing conventional wisdom, Greenfield said he didn=E2=80=
=99t think Disney would go outside the company to choose a successor. After=
 all, the job requires an extraordinary matrix of relationships and experie=
nces spanning Hollywood, Wall Street, Silicon Valley, and beyond=E2=80=94th=
e Disney C.E.O. needs to have the dexterity to deal with everything from in=
bound traffic from Bryan Lourd to offering notes on the latest Star Wars sc=
ript to managing the political exigencies from Tallahassee to Beijing=E2=80=
=A6 to say nothing of the talent and creative egos involved. =E2=80=9CThere=
=E2=80=99s something very specific
about Disney culture and process that I can=E2=80=99t imagine they really g=
o outside,=E2=80=9D Rich said. Indeed, Michael Eisner, the outsider, promot=
ed Iger from within. And Iger, of course, promoted Bob Chapek from within, =
much to his later regret.

But Brandon got Rich thinking differently. =E2=80=9CUnless the board says, =
You know what? These are different times, and we need a different skill set=
 to bring in to complement what we have,=E2=80=9D Brandon said. Rich picked=
 up on that idea immediately, and embraced it. =E2=80=9CYou=E2=80=99re righ=
t,=E2=80=9D Rich said. =E2=80=9CDo you pick somebody =E2=80=A6 with mobile =
advertising experience? Do you choose somebody with streaming experience? D=
o you go out of the box? Do you recognize that you have to bring in someone=
 from the outside because you don=E2=80=99t have the skill set internally? =
That is an awesome observation, Brandon=E2=80=94like, maybe it is time to d=
o something quote-unquote crazy and go outside.=E2=80=9D

Is it crazy? Of course not, but
the contenders aren=E2=80=99t obvious. Semi-outsiders Kevin Mayer and Tom S=
taggs, former longtime Disney executives and erstwhile heirs apparent, were=
 brought in by Iger last year as consultants to help ESPN through its trans=
ition to streaming, among other things. (I=E2=80=99m not sure what wisdom t=
hey bring on that specific topic but whatevs.) But Mayer and Staggs have pl=
enty of their own baggage=E2=80=94probably too much of it at this point to =
be considered viable candidates to succeed Iger, either together or alone. =
Their 3-year-old media company, Candle Media=E2=80=94which is backed by Bla=
ckstone to the tune of $1 billion and owns Moonbug Entertainment, Hello Sun=
shine, and Faraway Road Productions=E2=80=94massively overpaid for assets a=
nd has moved into what our friends at Semafor are calling the =E2=80=9Cgree=
n-eyeshade=E2=80=9D era thanks to its $1.4 billion of expensive debt and fa=
ltering operations. Disney would likely have to acquire Candle in order to =
bring the duo back into the fold=E2=80=94a long
putt indeed.

Even though it seems unfathomable that Mayer and Staggs would return to lea=
d Disney, is the idea of co-C.E.O.s viable in general? It might be just the=
 solution for a company that requires so many different areas of expertise =
in its leaders. On the other hand, dual C.E.O.s rarely work in corporate Am=
erica. True, it has worked at Netflix, which now has a market value of $323=
 billion, 85 percent higher than Disney=E2=80=99s. My bet is that Gorman wo=
uld be against that idea, given his Wall Street bias, where one leader at t=
he top is preferred. (Dual leaders worked at Goldman Sachs when it was stil=
l a private partnership.)

A less obvious idea would be a trusted, battle-tested chief executive, such=
 as Howard Schultz. But these seasoned corporate veteran types are often on=
 the other side of their prime. Schultz, a hypothetical example, is only tw=
o years younger than Iger, and would merely put Gorman back to work on a ne=
w plan in a couple more years.

And yet, an outsider may be what=E2=80=99s necessary to steer the company t=
hrough both its clear forthcoming challenges=E2=80=94the next recession, th=
e decline of linear TV, the rationalization of the streaming business, and =
the reimagination of the filmed entertainment business=E2=80=94and the ones=
 that can=E2=80=99t be predicted. I know Disney likes to view itself as an =
insular company that can only be led by someone who understands the culture=
=2E (I saw this firsthand when I worked=
 for Disney, back in my Lazard days, o=
n the restructuring of Euro Disney.) But the company could also use a fresh=
 voice who inspires confidence among investors and creditors, can define an=
d communicate a strategy for these times, and has enough self-confidence to=
 allow the very talented leaders of the various divisions=E2=80=94Pitaro, D=
=E2=80=99Amaro, Bergman, and Walden, among them=E2=80=94to do their jobs ef=
fectively. Gorman, in other words, needs all the time he can get.

