Gormanology

This, in fact, is a scenario that Gorman knows well. Despite the fact that =
he picked Ted Pick to lead Morgan from within the bank=E2=80=99s own ranks,=
 Gorman himself lived a different experience. He was an outsider at Morgan =
Stanley. After graduating in my class at Columbia Business School, he joine=
d McKinsey and spent the next 12 years there before moving to Merrill Lynch=
, in 1999, as chief marketing officer and then as head of its brokerage bus=
iness. In 2006, he left Merrill for Morgan Stanley, where he became preside=
nt and chief operating officer of its wealth management business. Four year=
s later, he was C.E.O., a job he held for the next 14 years. Morgan Stanley=
=E2=80=99s stock basically tripled during his tenure.

This is a familiar story, at least on Wall Street. Jamie Dimon had never wo=
rked a day in his life at JPMorgan Chase
before becoming the anointed successor to Bill Harrison in 2004, after JPMo=
rgan Chase acquired Dimon=E2=80=99s Bank One. I know a thing or two about d=
ysfunction at JPMorgan Chase in the years before Dimon=E2=80=94I was there =
and saw it firsthand. He was a complete outsider to what was an insular, sc=
lerotic culture, and he utterly transformed the place into a well-oiled mac=
hine, generating more than $50 billion of net income a year and accumulatin=
g a market value of nearly $640 billion. (He has his own unresolved success=
ion issues, as Dry Powder readers know well. But we=E2=80=99ll save that to=
pic for another day=E2=80=A6) All of which is to say that Disney is ripe fo=
r an outsider to come in and shake up the place.

And yet, one of my top Wall Street sources, with knowledge of the players, =
predicts that Iger=E2=80=99s successor will still come from inside the comp=
any=E2=80=94adding that while there=E2=80=99s a chance it would be an outsi=
der, he said he would be =E2=80=9Cvery
surprised.=E2=80=9D Another elite Wall Street player, who knows how Gorman =
thinks but doesn=E2=80=99t have a personal or financial stake in this situa=
tion, says if there were a =E2=80=9Csolid insider,=E2=80=9D he thinks that =
Disney would prefer to go in =E2=80=9Cthat direction.=E2=80=9D In my conver=
sations with my sources on the topic, the answers are similarly equivocal. =
The only thing they agree upon with certainty is that the decision to empow=
er Gorman is evidence of the market=E2=80=99s growing weariness with Iger=
=E2=80=99s reluctance to pass the baton once and for all.

Alas, the various enigmas around Gorman=E2=80=99s choice offer nothing but =
the one thing that Wall Street dislikes most: uncertainty. But here is one =
lesson that I=E2=80=99m sure is weighing on the former Morgan Stanley C.E.O=
=2E as he contemplates his portentous n=
ew task. After decades of choosing ins=
iders to run the company, six years ago the board of GE went outside to hir=
e Larry Culp=E2=80=94who ran Danaher, another conglomerate, and was briefly=
 on the
GE board of directors=E2=80=94to succeed John Flannery as C.E.O. Then Culp,=
 using Flannery=E2=80=99s strategic outline=E2=80=94=E2=80=9CProject Eisenh=
ower=E2=80=9D=E2=80=94proceeded to break the company up into three parts, e=
nding its life as America=E2=80=99s most successful conglomerate. Sometimes=
, over a long enough time horizon, the succession dramas that once only see=
med life-or-death really are existential.

