          <td style=3D"padding-bottom: 36px; color: #000000; font-size: 16p=
x; line-height: 30px; margin-top: 0; margin-bottom: 0;">Others agree. At th=
e end of August, before the Gorman announcement, LightShed Partners=E2=80=
=99 <b>Rich Greenfield</b> and <b>Brandon Ross</b> offered an interesting p=
relude about the topic on their podcast. Like many others, and in accordanc=
e with the prevailing conventional wisdom, Greenfield said he didn=E2=80=99=
t think Disney would go outside the company to choose a successor. After al=
l, the job requires an extraordinary matrix of relationships and experience=
s spanning Hollywood, Wall Street, Silicon Valley, and <i>beyond</i>=E2=80=
=94the Disney C.E.O. needs to have the dexterity to deal with everything fr=
om inbound traffic from <b>Bryan Lourd </b>to offering notes on the latest =
<i>Star Wars</i> script to managing the political exigencies from Tallahass=
ee to Beijing=E2=80=A6 to say nothing of the talent and creative egos invol=
ved. =E2=80=9CThere=E2=80=99s something very specific
about Disney culture and process that I can=E2=80=99t imagine they really g=
o outside,=E2=80=9D Rich said. Indeed, Michael Eisner, the outsider, promot=
ed Iger from within. And Iger, of course, promoted <b>Bob</b> <b>Chapek</b>=
 from within, much to his later regret.<br/><br/>But Brandon got Rich think=
ing differently. =E2=80=9CUnless the board says, <i>You know what? These ar=
e different times, and we need a different skill set to bring in to complem=
ent what we have</i>,=E2=80=9D Brandon said. Rich picked up on that idea im=
mediately, and embraced it. =E2=80=9CYou=E2=80=99re right,=E2=80=9D Rich sa=
id. =E2=80=9CDo you pick somebody =E2=80=A6 with mobile advertising experie=
nce? Do you choose somebody with streaming experience? Do you go out of the=
 box? Do you recognize that you have to bring in someone from the outside b=
ecause you don=E2=80=99t have the skill set internally? That is an awesome =
observation, Brandon=E2=80=94like, maybe it is time to do something quote-u=
nquote <i>crazy</i> and go outside.=E2=80=9D <br/><br/>Is it crazy? Of cour=
se not, but
the contenders aren=E2=80=99t obvious. Semi-outsiders <b>Kevin Mayer</b> an=
d <b>Tom Staggs</b>, former longtime Disney executives and erstwhile heirs =
apparent, were brought in by Iger last year as consultants to help ESPN thr=
ough its transition to streaming, among other things. (I=E2=80=99m not sure=
 what wisdom they bring on that specific topic but whatevs.) But Mayer and =
Staggs have plenty of their own baggage=E2=80=94probably too much of it at =
this point to be considered viable candidates to succeed Iger, either toget=
her or alone. Their 3-year-old media company, Candle Media=E2=80=94which is=
 backed by Blackstone to the tune of $1 billion and owns Moonbug Entertainm=
ent, Hello Sunshine, and Faraway Road Productions=E2=80=94massively overpai=
d for assets and has moved into what our friends at Semafor are calling the=
 =E2=80=9Cgreen-eyeshade=E2=80=9D era thanks to its $1.4 billion of expensi=
ve debt and faltering operations. Disney would likely have to acquire Candl=
e in order to bring the duo back into the fold=E2=80=94a long
putt indeed. <br/><br/>Even though it seems unfathomable that Mayer and Sta=
ggs would return to lead Disney, is the idea of co-C.E.O.s viable in genera=
l? It might be just the solution for a company that requires so many differ=
ent areas of expertise in its leaders. On the other hand, dual C.E.O.s rare=
ly work in corporate America. True, it has worked at Netflix, which now has=
 a market value of $323 billion, 85 percent higher than Disney=E2=80=99s. M=
y bet is that Gorman would be against that idea, given his Wall Street bias=
, where one leader at the top is preferred. (Dual leaders worked at Goldman=
 Sachs when it was still a private partnership.)<br/><br/>A less obvious id=
ea would be a trusted, battle-tested chief executive, such as <b>Howard Sch=
ultz</b>. But these seasoned corporate veteran types are often on the other=
 side of their prime. Schultz, a hypothetical example, is only two years yo=
unger than Iger, and would merely put Gorman back to work on a new plan in =
a couple more years.
<br/><br/>And yet, an outsider may be what=E2=80=99s necessary to steer the=
 company through both its clear forthcoming challenges=E2=80=94the next rec=
ession, the decline of linear TV, the rationalization of the streaming busi=
ness, and the reimagination of the filmed entertainment business=E2=80=94an=
d the ones that <i>can=E2=80=99t </i>be predicted. I know Disney likes to v=
iew itself as an insular company that can only be led by someone who unders=
tands the culture. (I saw this firsthand when I worked for Disney, back in =
my Lazard days, on the restructuring of Euro Disney.) But the company could=
 also use a fresh voice who inspires confidence among investors and credito=
rs, can define and communicate a strategy for these times, and has enough s=
elf-confidence to allow the very talented leaders of the various divisions=
=E2=80=94Pitaro, D=E2=80=99Amaro, Bergman, and Walden, among them=E2=80=94t=
o do their jobs effectively. Gorman, in other words, needs all the time he =
can get.<br/></td>
