          <td style=3D"padding-bottom: 36px; color: #000000; font-size: 16p=
x; line-height: 30px; margin-top: 0; margin-bottom: 0;">This, in fact, is a=
 scenario that Gorman knows well. Despite the fact that he picked <b>Ted Pi=
ck </b>to lead Morgan from within the bank=E2=80=99s own ranks, Gorman hims=
elf lived a different experience. He was an outsider at Morgan Stanley. Aft=
er graduating in my class at Columbia Business School, he joined McKinsey a=
nd spent the next 12 years there before moving to Merrill Lynch, in 1999, a=
s chief marketing officer and then as head of its brokerage business. In 20=
06, he left Merrill for Morgan Stanley, where he became president and chief=
 operating officer of its wealth management business. Four years later, he =
was C.E.O., a job he held for the next 14 years. Morgan Stanley=E2=80=99s s=
tock basically tripled during his tenure. <br/><br/>This is a familiar stor=
y, at least on Wall Street. <b>Jamie Dimon</b> had never worked a day in hi=
s life at JPMorgan Chase
before becoming the anointed successor to <b>Bill Harrison</b> in 2004, aft=
er JPMorgan Chase acquired Dimon=E2=80=99s Bank One. I know a thing or two =
about dysfunction at JPMorgan Chase in the years before Dimon=E2=80=94I was=
 there and saw it firsthand. He was a complete outsider to what was an insu=
lar, sclerotic culture, and he utterly transformed the place into a well-oi=
led machine, generating more than <i>$50 billion</i> of net income a year a=
nd accumulating a market value of nearly $640 billion. (He has his own unre=
solved succession issues, as Dry Powder readers know well. But we=E2=80=99l=
l save that topic for another day=E2=80=A6) All of which is to say that Dis=
ney is ripe for an outsider to come in and shake up the place. <br/><br/>An=
d yet, one of my top Wall Street sources, with knowledge of the players, pr=
edicts that Iger=E2=80=99s successor will still come from <i>inside</i> the=
 company=E2=80=94adding that while there=E2=80=99s a <i>chance</i> it would=
 be an outsider, he said he would be =E2=80=9Cvery
surprised.=E2=80=9D Another elite Wall Street player, who knows how Gorman =
thinks but doesn=E2=80=99t have a personal or financial stake in this situa=
tion, says if there were a =E2=80=9Csolid insider,=E2=80=9D he thinks that =
Disney would prefer to go in =E2=80=9Cthat direction.=E2=80=9D In my conver=
sations with my sources on the topic, the answers are similarly equivocal. =
The only thing they agree upon with certainty is that the decision to empow=
er Gorman is evidence of the market=E2=80=99s growing weariness with Iger=
=E2=80=99s reluctance to pass the baton once and for all. <br/><br/>Alas, t=
he various enigmas around Gorman=E2=80=99s choice offer nothing but the one=
 thing that Wall Street dislikes most: uncertainty. But here is one lesson =
that I=E2=80=99m sure is weighing on the former Morgan Stanley C.E.O. as he=
 contemplates his portentous new task. After decades of choosing insiders t=
o run the company, six years ago the board of GE went outside to hire <b>La=
rry Culp</b>=E2=80=94who ran Danaher, another conglomerate, and was briefly=
 on the
GE board of directors=E2=80=94to succeed <b>John</b> <b>Flannery</b> as C.E=
=2EO. Then Culp, using Flanner=
y=E2=80=99s strategic outline=E2=80=94=E2=80=9C=
Project Eisenhower=E2=80=9D=E2=80=94proceeded to break the company up into =
three parts, ending its life as America=E2=80=99s most successful conglomer=
ate. Sometimes, over a long enough time horizon, the succession dramas that=
 once only <i>seemed</i> life-or-death really are existential.<br/></td>
         </tr>
